    <h3 class="title"><a href="/selling-empty-middle-seats-dutch-auction#comment-12798" class="active">Complexity is the problem</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Mon, 2011-04-25 18:23.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>I do agree that initial thoughts are complex.   I think the core realization &#8212; that there are going to be a limited number of empty middles on a nearly full plane, and there should be a system to allocate them next to those who want them the most &#8212; is a good one, and the challenge is how to do so more simply.</p>

<p>However I think the basic form (no pairing attempted) is simple enough and wrote instructions for how it would work.  One way to approach pairing is to say the seat now belongs to the person who won the bid, and they do not have to share it with the person on the other side in any way, and are free to even charge them if they want to rest their papers there, use the tray etc.   There might develop an ethic of how this works though I think most people would be magnanimous.  Others might find fair to pay.</p>
</div>
