    <h3 class="title"><a href="/selling-empty-middle-seats-dutch-auction#comment-12807" class="active">Travel Pods</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/joel-upchurch" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">Joel Upchurch</a> on Sat, 2011-04-30 19:13.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>It seems to me that the most elegant solution would be to have travel pods that the passengers could be loaded into and then the passengers could simply be treated as another type of cargo. The passengers could check themselves in at the same time that they check in their luggage. Some passengers might object to the lack of mobility and the coffin-like dimension of the pods, but it seems to me that that could addressed with a mild sedative and I think most people would agree that actual unconsciousness would be preferable to usual air travel experience. A cursory examination of the current cabin environment causes one to realize that most of the space in the cabin is wasted space. A pod flight would be able to carry significantly more passengers at a lower cost once we eliminate aisles, seats, galleys, bathrooms, flight attendants and unused air space.</p>
<p>Since passengers would travel in the pod naked and attached to a catheter, it should virtually eliminate any risk of hijacking. The pods would be equipped with VR equipment providing the passengers with a variety of 3D entertainment, especially for passengers with World of Warcraft accounts. Different types of recreation would be available for passenger who upgrade to the deluxe catheters. Since there may some problems with passengers who refuse to be decanted at their destination, the transition to ground based reality will be eased by spending the last half hour of the flight in a VR simulation of the Department of Motor Vehicles.</p>
<p>I would like to point out for the humor impaired, that the preceding in intended to be mostly satirical in nature.</p>
</div>
