  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/selling-empty-middle-seats-dutch-auction#comment-12836" class="active">Thoughts on your idea</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by Kevin Postlewaite (not verified) on Wed, 2011-05-11 16:10.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>-It may not be too difficult to implement (I've already heard of airline checkin kiosks where they ask how much you would demand to receive to bump you from the flight if it's overbooked, not much different to add an option to price an empty middle seat)<br />
-Why do airlines price window/aisle seats the same as middle seats anyway?<br />
-If airlines allow one to raise the chances of an empty middle seat, this may lower the price some people are willing to pay to fly business/first class so this loss would need to taken into account when considering whether it's financially worthwhile for them (I think it would still be worthwhile)</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links"><li class="first last comment_reply"><a href="/comment/reply/1113/12836" class="comment_reply">reply</a></li>
</ul></div>
  </div>
<div class="indented"><a id="comment-12837"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/selling-empty-middle-seats-dutch-auction#comment-12837" class="active">Compete with biz class</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Wed, 2011-05-11 17:27.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>I do agree there is a risk that they could see these seats as competition for business class.  United at least used to offer an empty middle if available to elite flyers, and sort of do still &#8212; except it never works because they fill planes too well.</p>

<p>Part of it would depend on whether companies let people place high bids on getting these empty middles with corporate money.   If they did, the bids might get quite high so only corporate users get it.   But the unsure nature of the bid would probably not be suitable for companies that have decided to give staff business class.  I think it would only affect people flying on their own dime.</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links"><li class="first last comment_reply"><a href="/comment/reply/1113/12837" class="comment_reply">reply</a></li>
</ul></div>
  </div>
</div><a id="comment-13473"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/selling-empty-middle-seats-dutch-auction#comment-13473" class="active">a fact and an opinion</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by Anon (not verified) on Wed, 2012-02-29 18:39.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>This is not a dutch auction.  A dutch auction would be the airline sets a high price and allows people to take that price, if no one takes the price, the price is lowered and bidders are again allowed to take the new price.  The process continues in this manner until the items (seats) are sold.  The first one to bid wins in this case.</p>
<p>I think airline travel should partially be paid by weight.  If you weigh more, you pay more.  A heavier plane will use up more fuel than a lighter plane.  And fuel is a large component in flight costs.  This could incentivize heavy people to lose weight(healthier and more room for everyone); disincentivize heavy people from flying(more room for everyone), or at least you'll know the person taking up half of your shoulder space paid more.  Some might think this is discriminatory; you have the power to change your weight though (of course, it's not easy).  Some might think this is cruel.  We shouldn't make fun of people's weight, but we should be able to talk about it truthfully.  It is unhealthy and impedes on their own lifestyle as well as other's.  If someone is happy with that lifestyle, good for them.  They should also be happy to pay more.</p>
<p>Aside from that, I've always been a fan of the travel pods idea.  This would require a drastic rewrite in emergency guidelines though, unless each pod could convert into a glider/sub and be ejected from the plane...sweet!</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links"><li class="first last comment_reply"><a href="/comment/reply/1113/13473" class="comment_reply">reply</a></li>
</ul></div>
  </div>
<div class="indented"><a id="comment-13476"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/selling-empty-middle-seats-dutch-auction#comment-13476" class="active">Not a dutch</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Thu, 2012-03-01 23:07.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>Technically correct, it&#8217;s a uniform price auction (of which the Dutch auction is an example.)  eBay calls the sealed bid uniform price auction a dutch auction which has been redefining the term.</p>

<p>You could try to charge based on weight (and amount of baggage) but I suspect you would get customer revolt, they would reject to being weighed.   And while the passenger&#8217;s weight does cost some fuel, it&#8217;s not a huge part of the ticket price.   On top of this, there are are those who weigh more for medical reasons and genetics, and of course men weight more than women so it would be a sex discrimination.  </p>

<p>Not likely to fly!</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links"><li class="first last comment_reply"><a href="/comment/reply/1113/13476" class="comment_reply">reply</a></li>
</ul></div>
